05027nam a22006735i 9780520969902DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020004309  a97805209699027 a10.1525/97805209699022doi  a(DE-B1597)572437  a(OCoLC)1142886440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aML410.F27 4aML410.F27bR86 2020 7aMUS0500002bisacsh04a782.4/70922231 aRumph, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Faure Song Cycles :bPoetry and Music, 1861-1921 /cStephen Rumph. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Music Examples -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Romancing the mélodie A Hugo Cycle? -- t2. Ascending Parnassus Poème d'un jour, op. 21 -- t3. The Discovery of Music Cinq mélodies "de Venise," op. 58 -- t4. Wagnerian correspondances La bonne chanson, op. 61 -- t5. Theatrical Song La chanson d'Ève, op. 95 -- t6. Writing in the Sand Le jardin clos, op. 106 -- t7. Neoclassical Voyages Mirages, op. 113 and L'horizon chimérique, op. 118 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGabriel Fauré's mélodies offer an inexhaustible variety of style and expression that have made them the foundation of the French art song repertoire. During the second half of his long career, Fauré composed all but a handful of his songs within six carefully integrated cycles. Fauré moved systematically through his poetic contemporaries, exhausting Baudelaire's Les fleurs du mal before immersing himself in the Parnassian poets. He would set nine poems by Armand Silvestre in swift succession (1878-84), seventeen by Paul Verlaine (1887-94), and eighteen by Charles Van Lerberghe (1906-14). As an artist deeply engaged with some of the most important cultural issues of the period, Fauré reimagined his musical idiom with each new poet and school, and his song cycles show the same sensitivity to the poetic material. Far more than Debussy, Ravel, or Poulenc, he crafted his song cycles as integrated works, reordering poems freely and using narratives, key schemes, and even leitmotifs to unify the individual songs. The Fauré Song Cycles explores the peculiar vision behind each synthesis of music and verse, revealing the astonishing imagination and insight of Fauré's musical readings. This book offers not only close readings of Fauré's musical works but an interdisciplinary study of how he responded to the changing schools and aesthetic currents of French poetry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aMusic and literaturezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMusic and literaturezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSong cyclesy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSong cyclesy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSongsy19th centuryxAnalysis, appreciation. 0aSongsy20th centuryxAnalysis, appreciation. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969902zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978052096